et: Middle English {it}fondrer{/it} "to fall to the ground, stumble, sink," borrowed from Anglo-French {it}fundrer{/it} "to destroy," probably back-formation from {it}enfondrer, esfondrer, affondrer{/it} "to sink, send to the bottom," prefixed forms based on Old French {it}-fondrer,{/it} going back to Vulgar Latin {it}*-fundorāre,{/it} verbal derivative of Late Latin {it}fundor-,{/it} variant stem of Latin {it}fundus{/it} "bottom, base" {ma}{mat|bottom:1|}{/ma}

The simple verb {it}fundrer{/it} (as opposed to prefixed forms) is marginally attested in Anglo-French, its senses partially merged with {it}fondre{/it} going back to Latin {it}fundere{/it} (see {et_link|found:5|found:5}), which in addition to its basic meanings "to pour, cast" had already in Classical Latin the extended meanings "to scatter, disperse, rout" and "to lay low, slay."
